  "prompt": "Why do I look very hot in the mirror, but pretty bad in pictures?",
  "response": "It's a common experience to feel like you look better in the mirror than in photos, and there are several reasons for this:\n\n1. **The Mirror Flips Your Image**: What you see in the mirror is a reversed (flipped) version of your face. Since you're used to seeing this flipped version, photos (which show your face as others see it, unflipped) can look unfamiliar or less \"right\" to you.\n\n2. **Dynamic vs. Static Perception**: In the mirror, you see yourself in motion, with natural expressions and movements. Photos, on the other hand, capture a single, static moment, which might not represent your appearance as accurately as you'd like.\n\n3. **Lighting and Angles**: Mirrors often provide consistent lighting and an angle you're used to, which can be flattering. In photos, lighting can be harsh or unflattering, and angles might not be ideal, making you appear less attractive than you feel.\n\n4. **Lens Distortion**: Cameras, especially on smartphones, can distort your features due to the focal length of the lens. Wide-angle lenses, in particular, can exaggerate facial features (e.g., making noses look larger), which isn't how you appear in real life.\n\n5. **Psychological Bias**: You\u2019re naturally more critical of yourself in photos because you\u2019re scrutinizing them more closely than you would in the mirror. Additionally, the \"mere-exposure effect\" means you prefer the version of yourself you see most often\u2014the mirror version.\n\n6. **Pose and Expression**: In the mirror, you can adjust your pose and expression in real time to look your best. In photos, you might not always nail the perfect pose or smile, leading to less flattering results.\n\n7. **Unconscious Mirror Habits**: Over time, you\u2019ve likely developed subtle habits in the mirror (e.g., tilting your head or positioning yourself in a certain way) that make you look your best. These habits might not translate to photos.\n\nThe good news is that the version of yourself you see in the mirror is likely closer to how others see you in real life. Photos often don\u2019t capture your true appearance due to the factors mentioned above. If you want to improve how you look in photos, experiment with lighting, angles, and poses to find what works best for you!",
  "temperature": 1.0,
